        <dc:title>High‐Resolution Simulations of the Plunging Region in a Pseudo‐Newtonian Potential: Dependence on Numerical Resolution and Field Topology</dc:title>
        <dcterms:abstract>New three-dimensional magnetohydrodynamic simulations of accretion disk dynamics in a pseudoNewtonian Paczynç ski-Wiita potential are presented. These have Ðner resolution in the inner disk than any previously reported. Finer resolution leads to increased magnetic Ðeld strength, greater accretion rate, and greater Ñuctuations in the accretion rate. One simulation begins with a purely poloidal magnetic Ðeld, the other with a purely toroidal Ðeld. Compared to the poloidal initial Ðeld simulation, a purely toroidal initial Ðeld takes longer to reach saturation of the magnetorotational instability and produces less turbulence and weaker magnetic Ðeld energies. For both initial Ðeld conÐgurations, magnetic stresses continue across the marginally stable orbit ; measured in units corresponding to the ShakuraSunyaev a-parameter, the stress grows from D0.1 in the disk body to as much as D10 deep in the plunging region. Matter passing the inner boundary of the simulation has D10% greater binding energy and D10% smaller angular momentum than it did at the marginally stable orbit. Both the mass accretion rate and the integrated stress Ñuctuate widely on a broad range of timescales.</dcterms:abstract>
